value.value: An occurrence which is relatively low.
A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the severity of infectious disease caused by the bearer in a target organism.
A virulence that is relatively low.
A virulence that is relatively high.
A quality which inheres in a molecular entity, a single molecule, atom, ion, radical etc.
A quality that has a value that is increased compared to normal or average.
A quality that has a value that is decreased compared to normal or average.
A quality of a process that has a value that is decreased compared to normal or average.
A quality of an object that has a value that is decreased compared to normal or average.
A quality of a process that has a value that is increased compared to normal or average.
A quality of an object that has a value that is increased compared to normal or average.
A temporal distribution pattern of process occurrences within a regulation/reference process.
The temporal relation between the end of the process with respect to a reference process.
The temporal relation between the start of the process with respect to a reference process.
A nucleate quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having one or more nucleus.
The ability of a pathogen to produce an infectious disease or disorder in an another organism.

definition.value: A rate which is relatively normal.
A quality of an object that has a value that is normal or average.
A concentration which is relatively normal or average.
A resistance to a stimulus which is relatively normal or average
A sensitivity toward an external stimulus which is relatively normal or average
A size quality which is relatively normal or average
A length quality which is relatively normal or average
A quality of a process that has a value that is normal or average.
A virulence which is relatively normal or average
A duration quality of a process which is relatively normal.
An occurrence which is relatively normal.
A sensitivity of a process which is relatively normal.
A quality of continuant that exist at the anatomical level of organisation and anything under it. This includes, but is not limited to, cells , tissues, and components.
Any of the set of observable characteristics arising from the interaction of a potentially pathogenic organism with a host organism.

This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.
Any of the set of observable characteristics of a single organism resulting from the interaction of its genotype with the environment.

This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.
A single organism phenotype that is observed at the level of a tissue (eg leaf, inflorescence, ear or kidney).

This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.
A phenotype where the ability of a pathogen, to produce an infectious disease in another organism is unaffected (i.e the same as wild-type, it could be pathogenic or non-pathogenic).
For use in the annotation extension infective ability. Can only apply to changes in the pathogen.
A phenotype that is relevant to pathogenicity. Pathogenicity is the ability of an organism, a pathogen, to produce an infectious disease in another organism
Can only apply to changes in the pathogen. Pathogenicity is a qualitative concept.
A phenotype where the ability of a pathogen, to produce an infectious disease in another organism is obtained (pathogenicity was absent and is now present).

For use in the annotation extension infective ability. Can only apply to changes in the pathogen. Note that this ability to cause pathogenicity is a feature of the pathogen. Therefore gain/loss of pathogenicity should never be dependent on changes to the host genotype, only on changes to the pathogen genotype. If you are annotating changes in disease presence or absence dependent on the changes to the host consider increased/decreased virulence phenotypes.
A phenotype where the ability of a pathogen, to produce an infectious disease in another organism is abolished (pathogenicity was present and is now absent).

For use in the annotation extension infective ability. Can only apply to changes in the pathogen. Note that this ability to cause pathogenicity is a feature of the pathogen. Therefore gain/loss of pathogenicity should never be dependent on changes to the host genotype, only on changes to the pathogen genotype. If you are annotating changes in disease presence or absence dependent on the changes to the host consider increased/decreased virulence phenotypes. Note that avirulence means loss of/abolished virulence in plant pathology terminology.

A phenotype that is relevant to virulence. Virulence is the degree to which a pathogen (species or strain) is able to cause infectious disease in another organism. (Virulence is observed where pathogenicity is present).
Can apply to changes in the pathogen or the host. Virulence is a quantitative concept

A phenotype where the degree to which a pathogen (species or strain) is able to cause infectious disease in another organism is unchanged (i.e. the same degree of infectious disease as wild-type interaction).
For use in the annotation extension infective ability. Can apply to changes in the pathogen or the host.
A phenotype where the degree to which a pathogen (species or strain) is able to cause infectious disease in another organism is increased (i.e. more symptoms than normal).
For use in the annotation extension infective ability. Can apply to changes in the pathogen or the host.
A phenotype where the degree to which a pathogen (species or strain) is able to cause infectious disease in another organism is decreased (i.e. fewer symptoms than normal).
For use in the annotation extension infective ability. Can apply to changes in the pathogen or the host.
A single organism phenotype which is normal (i.e. the same as wild-type).
A single organism phenotype which is abnormal (i.e. different than wild-type).

label.value: lipid droplets present in decreased numbers

definition.value: A single species phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells contain fewer lipid droplets than normal.
A lethal single organism cell level phenotype resulting from altering a gene product that is essential for the life of the organism.

A growth phenotype which describes the sensitivity of individuals or populations after exposure to a specific chemical. Typically, organisms are deemed sensitive to a chemical if they stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of the chemical that allows wild type individuals or populations to grow.

A growth phenotype which describes the resistance of individuals or populations after exposure to a specific chemical. Typically, organisms are deemed resistant to a chemical if they survive at a concentration of the chemical that does not allow wild type individuals or populations to grow.

label.value: pathogen penetration across the barrier present

definition.value: A single species pathogen penetration phenotype in which pathogen penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane is present.

label.value: normal pathogen growth after penetration of the barrier

definition.value: A single species phenotype in which the pathogen's ability to contine to grow after penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane in an in vitro assay is normal (i.e indistinguishable from wild type).
